Introduction to Likelihood, concept of likelihood, maximum likelihood estimators and their properties. Linear Models: Least Squares and maximum likelihood. The Confidence Interval for model parameters. The Hypothesis Test for model parameters, ANOVA, and model diagnostics.

getCourses.Description: Statistical modelling provides methods for analysing data to gain insight into real-world problems. The aim of this unit is to introduce a wide range of fundamental statistical modelling and data analysis techniques, and demonstrate the role they play in drawing inferences in real-world problems. This unit is designed around the exploration of contemporary and important issues through the analysis of real data sets, while simultaneously and necessarily building your statistical modelling expertise. You will learn how to propose research questions, analyse real data sets to attempt to answer these questions, and draw inferences and conclusions based on your findings. The importance of ethical considerations when dealing with real data sets will be emphasised. The R programming language will be introduced, and you will gain experience and build your expertise in using this industry-leading software to conduct statistical analyses.

getCourses.Learning_Approaches:
This unit is designed around the exploration of contemporary and important issues through the analysis of real data sets, while simultaneously and necessarily building your statistical modelling expertise. While lectures focus on the required mathematical and statistical content, weekly individual-based computer labs and group-based collaborative learning workshops focus on the essential skills of scientific enquiry. In these sessions you will learn how to propose research questions, manipulate and analyse real data sets to attempt to answer these questions, and draw inferences and conclusions based on your findings. The importance of ethical considerations when dealing with real data sets will be emphasised.

The R programming language will be introduced, and you will gain experience and build your expertise in using this industry-leading software to conduct statistical analyses.

getCourses.Description: An algorithm is a step-by-step set of instructions or rules designed to perform a specific task or solve a particular problem. In computer science, algorithms are crucial for designing efficient and effective solutions to various computational problems.

Web computing, also known as cloud computing, refers to the delivery of computing services over the internet. Instead of relying on a local server or a personal computer to handle applications, storage, or processing power, users can access these resources remotely through the web. test course

This unit introduces probability and shows you how to apply its concepts to solve practical problems. The unit will lay the foundations for further studies in statistics, operations research and other areas of mathematics and help you to develop your problem-solving and modelling skills. The topics covered include: basic probability rules, conditional probability and independence, discrete and continuous random variables, bivariate distributions, central limit theorem, and introduction to Markov chains. This unit is appropriate for those requiring an introduction to, or a refresher in, probability. The concepts in this unit will be extended in MXB241.

This unit builds on the gentle introduction to programming provided in IFB104, EGB103 or MZB126. In those units students learn how algorithms are constructed by combining the logical structures of sequence, selection and iteration. Students also learn how functions can be used to abstract and reuse sections of code. These concepts are reinforced in this unit and extended with additional applications of abstraction necessary to combat complexity when building larger systems. Object-oriented principles are introduced where the program is structured around classes of objects that are identified from the real-world providing a high-level architecture that is better able to stand the test of time as requirements evolve throughout the lifetime of the system. This unit provides the foundation for the other more advanced and specialized programming units.

Your course overview:
Course chat

Go here to introduce yourself to your tutor and classmates.
You can also post questions about any topic at any time here and chat with your classmates.
Modules and assignments

A new module opens up every Monday morning. Here you’ll find your weekly audio lessons, handouts, bonus exercises and the assignment.
Assignments are due by 11.59pm each Sunday night (Sydney/Melbourne time).
Technical support
If you’re stuck or need help with anything in your online classroom, you can contact us via courses@writerscentre.com.au.


FAQ: What's the difference between the assignments and the bonus exercises?
In this course, there are:

Assignments
Bonus exercises
There is an important distinction between the two.

Assignments
You have an assignment to complete and submit in each module. If you submit these by the due dates, you will receive feedback from your tutor.

Exercises
Each module also has bonus exercises. These are designed to help you flex your writing muscles and practice what you're learning. After all, the only way you get better at anything is to practice.

You do not submit exercises and will not receive feedback on them.

We’ve designed exercises specifically to help you become more aware of all the elements you need to consider when you are writing. Remember, it’s not just about getting words on the page, it’s also about the thinking you do – about your characters, your story, your point of view and so on.

You can complete the exercises along with the module, or come back and work on them later. (Remember, you have access to this classroom for 12 months from the course start date so you can definitely come back later to go through the exercises if you are pressed for time during the course.)

In summary:

Assignments: You WILL be receiving feedback on your assignments submitted by the due date.
Exercises: You will not be receiving feedback on these.

getCourses.Content:
Welcome to Writing Young Adult Fiction Create gripping, enthralling stories for teenagers
Tutor: Pamela Freeman
Format: Online self-paced course
Length: 5 modules
Access for: 12 months from your enrollment date


The popularity of books for the young adult market has exploded in the last decade, becoming one of the most successful areas of the industry. But what is it exactly – and who is it aimed at? What special skills or knowledge do you need to write successfully for this very sophisticated readership?


This course is designed for writers who intend to write fiction for this age group: it will help you improve your skills and gain a deeper understanding of this exciting area of publishing.
Writing for young adults (that is, 14-19 year olds) is challenging, absorbing and rewarding in different ways to writing for younger readers or adults.


YA readers are passionate and demanding – if they love your work, they love it completely. But how do you engage that passion? And how do you meet the demands of an audience highly versed in narrative but not so experienced in life? This course will help you develop your ideas and hone your skills so you can create amazing, enthralling stories that teenagers will love.


Publishers are always on the lookout for the next big YA phenomenon. But they’re also on the lookout for the quieter, more personal stories that teens keep reading, year after year. This course will help you define what you’re offering to publishers – and equip you to deepen its appeal to teen readers.


YA isn’t a genre, it’s a readership. YA publishing covers all genres, from speculative fiction to heart-wrenching love stories, from mysteries to family dramas. It’s also common for YA books to be in a series, whether that’s an ongoing series, or a trilogy. The tricky part of this is structure – so this course also delves into how to structure a multi-book series, as well as looking at the classic 3-act structure for standalone novels.


And finally, the gatekeepers…YA novels are bought as often by adults as by teens, so what are the rules? What will make a librarian say, “Not suitable” for their borrowers? How much should you censor? There are rules, but they may not be what you think – and they are different in different countries. Writing for YA will make sure you understand these (often unspoken) guidelines, so you have the best possible chance of getting published.
getCourses.Description: Create gripping, enthralling stories for teenagers
getCourses.Learning_Outcomes:
You will learn to:
  • understand exactly what a YA novel is and does – and what the ‘rules’ are in YA fiction
  • Develop great characters readers will identify with
  • create an engaging voice for your main characters
  • craft a cast of lively, believable characters who will enrich your story
  • incorporate the key elements of a strong structure and a storytelling mode that works for this audience
  • Improving your writing through the exercises, guiding towards writing a book which YA readers will obsess over
  • writing for YA will help you to turn your YA novel into a gripping, enthralling, emotional story that will grab its readers and never let them go
  • you’ll finish the course more confident and far better equipped to succeed in this exciting but challenging area of publishing.
